Subject: [PATCH] x86_64: fix initrd placement and 64-bit addressing
Base: v1.19.4

x86 guests with enough memory place the initrd above 4 GiB, but only the
low 32 bits of its address are written to the Linux boot parameters. Linux
then reads unrelated low memory and silently treats the initrd as empty.

Populate the boot protocol's extended ramdisk address and size fields. Also
keep the initrd wholly within either the low or high RAM bank so guests near
the 32-bit MMIO boundary do not place it in or across the MMIO hole. Return
the existing initrd load error when no bank is large enough, and propagate
guest-memory write failures instead of panicking.

